{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774366222,"nonce":"J/fqs/rshulpEXAggQSG0afQJUA=","message":"## Run 3: CVaR 10% results (TPU v4-8)\n\n### CVaR 10% with running_cost loss\n- Loss: 32.3 → 16.6 (49% reduction — less than standard's 91%)\n- Endpoint error: 0.109 (vs 0.007 for standard)\n- Peak speed: 3.18 (vs 3.33 for standard)\n- Final speed: 0.27 (vs 0.019 for standard)\n- **SISU 0→1 peak velocity: -0.9% (NO increase)**\n\n### Interpretation\nCVaR makes training harder (optimizing worst 10% of trials) but does NOT produce SISU-dependent peak velocity. The model reaches less accurately and with similar speed regardless of SISU.\n\n### Summary across ALL conditions tested\n\n| Condition | Loss | Ep err | Peak vel | SISU velocity effect |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| running_cost (standard) | 32→3 | 0.007 | 3.33 | -0.3% |\n| CVaR 10% (running_cost) | 32→17 | 0.109 | 3.18 | -0.9% |\n| softmin | DIVERGED | - | - | - |\n| default | DIVERGED | - | - | - |\n| combined | 11→5 | 0.152 | 2.06 | - |\n\nNone show increased peak velocity with SISU.\n\n### Still training (TPU)\n- running_cost_nn1e4 (nn_output=1e-4, higher control cost)\n- running_cost_nn1e6 (nn_output=1e-6, lower control cost)\n\nThese vary the effort penalty, which controls the speed-accuracy tradeoff. Different control costs may affect the absolute peak velocity but are unlikely to create SISU-dependent modulation.\n\n### Analysis\nThe lack of SISU velocity effect across all conditions — including CVaR (worst-case emphasis) — suggests the issue is not just the training objective. Possible remaining explanations:\n1. The SISU input has minimal influence on the network's learned policy\n2. The perturbation structure (gusts) doesn't create sufficient incentive for velocity changes\n3. The model architecture (GRU + point mass) can compensate for perturbations without changing velocity\n4. The adaptive control cost (currently disabled) may be needed to create the right tradeoff\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}